WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:05.244
Tuberculosis is a contagious, infectious
disease caused by mycobacterium tuberculosis

2
00:00:05.244 --> 00:00:08.805
that primarily affects the lungs but can
involve other organs.

3
00:00:09.564 --> 00:00:12.425
For respiratory therapists, TB is not just
about infection.

4
00:00:12.784 --> 00:00:15.564
It's about understanding transmission,
recognizing risk,

5
00:00:15.765 --> 00:00:18.784
and managing both respiratory status and
infection control.

6
00:00:19.125 --> 00:00:23.504
The disease spreads through airborne
droplet nuclei when an infected person coughs,

7
00:00:23.825 --> 00:00:24.545
sneezes, or speaks.

8
00:00:25.184 --> 00:00:28.145
Once inhaled, the bacteria reach the
alveoli where they trigger

9
00:00:28.145 --> 00:00:29.125
an immune response.

10
00:00:29.405 --> 00:00:32.084
In many patients, this leads to latent
tuberculosis,

11
00:00:32.365 --> 00:00:34.924
where the bacteria are contained but not
eliminated.

12
00:00:35.825 --> 00:00:38.444
These patients are asymptomatic and not
infectious.

13
00:00:39.125 --> 00:00:40.965
However, if the immune system weakens,

14
00:00:41.365 --> 00:00:43.904
latent TB can reactivate into active
disease.

15
00:00:44.625 --> 00:00:47.564
Active tuberculosis is where RTs play a
critical role.

16
00:00:48.305 --> 00:00:50.685
Patients may present with chronic cough,
hemoptysis,

17
00:00:51.084 --> 00:00:52.764
fever, night sweats, weight loss,

18
00:00:52.845 --> 00:00:53.444
and fatigue.

19
00:00:53.865 --> 00:00:57.005
From a respiratory standpoint, you must
assess oxygenation,

20
00:00:57.185 --> 00:00:58.904
work of breathing, breath sounds, and

21
00:00:58.904 --> 00:01:03.365
overall clinical stability, but also
immediately think infection control.

22
00:01:04.005 --> 00:01:06.425
One of the most important first steps is
airborne isolation.

23
00:01:07.184 --> 00:01:10.944
This includes placing the patient in a
negative pressure room and ensuring proper use

24
00:01:10.944 --> 00:01:12.404
of N95 respirators.

25
00:01:13.125 --> 00:01:16.205
Missing this step is a major safety risk
for staff and other patients.

26
00:01:16.985 --> 00:01:20.404
Diagnostics focus on confirming infection
and infectiousness.

27
00:01:21.004 --> 00:01:23.925
Chest x-ray often shows upper-lobed
infiltrates or cavitation.

28
00:01:24.745 --> 00:01:27.864
Sputum samples are essential for acid-fast
bacilli smear and culture.

29
00:01:27.864 --> 00:01:30.785
A positive smear suggests the patient is
infectious.

30
00:01:31.684 --> 00:01:36.345
Additional tests like nucleic acid
amplification help confirm the diagnosis more rapidly.

31
00:01:36.625 --> 00:01:40.705
Treatment involves long-term multidrug
therapy, typically including isoniazid,

32
00:01:41.205 --> 00:01:43.605
rifampin, pyrazinamide, and ethambutol.

33
00:01:44.184 --> 00:01:47.084
Adherence is critical, which is why
directly observed therapy is

34
00:01:47.084 --> 00:01:47.724
often used.

35
00:01:48.305 --> 00:01:51.065
From an RT perspective, you may assist
with sputum induction,

36
00:01:51.684 --> 00:01:54.544
monitor respiratory status, and support
airway clearance when needed.

37
00:01:54.544 --> 00:01:58.324
Red flags include worsening hypoxemia,
extensive lung involvement,

38
00:01:58.764 --> 00:02:01.324
massive hemoptysis, or signs of
respiratory failure.

39
00:02:01.985 --> 00:02:05.264
In these cases, escalation may involve
oxygen therapy or even

40
00:02:05.264 --> 00:02:08.945
ventilatory support, but always with
strict airborne precautions in place.

41
00:02:09.485 --> 00:02:11.604
For board exams, remember this core
pattern.

42
00:02:12.365 --> 00:02:16.544
Chronic symptoms plus weight loss and
night sweats should immediately raise suspicion for TB.

43
00:02:17.205 --> 00:02:20.164
Always prioritize isolation first, then
diagnostics,

44
00:02:20.225 --> 00:02:21.125
then treatment.

45
00:02:21.125 --> 00:02:23.205
The key takeaway is this.

46
00:02:23.604 --> 00:02:26.985
Tuberculosis is both a respiratory and
public health emergency.

47
00:02:27.684 --> 00:02:29.684
As an RT, your role is to protect the
patient,

48
00:02:30.324 --> 00:02:33.244
protect yourself, and break the chain of
transmission while supporting

49
00:02:33.244 --> 00:02:34.145
respiratory function.

